<subSubSection id="2DF0ACA1FFFBFFC4FF71FA75FB3BF9FF" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFBFFC4FF71FA75FDE4FA6F" blockId="19.[151,1437,1410,1617]" box="[151,537,1447,1473]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
(
<figureCitation id="FDD1E3AFFFFBFFC4FF79FA75FF05FA6F" box="[159,248,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="67.[151,250,1945,1969]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,196,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@67.[184,1403,181,1922]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURE 14. Southeast Asian Eudocima and Eudocima tyrannus group adults (dorsal aspect)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6605535" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6605535/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 14</figureCitation>
: A–B, 20: J, 26: E, 32: B)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFBFFC4FF71FA19FB3BF9FF" blockId="19.[151,1437,1410,1617]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The hindwings are very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFBFFC4FDC6FA19FD3FFA4B" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[544,706,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sikhimensis">
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFBFFC4FDC6FA19FD3FFA4B" box="[544,706,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. sikhimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however the forewing apex is not falcate, the forewing color is predominately bright rufous rather than olive, and the third segment of the palpi is shorter and less spatulate. The greenish forewing mottling is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFBFFC4FDBEF9C1FD06F983" baseAuthorityName="Prout" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[600,763,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bathyglypta">
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFBFFC4FDBEF9C1FD06F983" box="[600,763,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. bathyglypta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the tornal hook and anal flap are much less pronounced. This rare species is found in peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFBFFC4FDB3F9E5FD43F9FF" box="[597,702,1591,1617]" name="Malaysia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, Sumatra and Borneo (
<bibRefCitation id="017B82DBFFFBFFC4FC58F9E5FB47F9FF" author="Zilli, A. &amp; Hogenes, W." box="[958,1210,1591,1617]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="153 - 207" refId="ref41799" refString="Zilli, A. &amp; Hogenes, W. (2002) An annotated list of the fruit-piercing moth genus Eudocima Billberg, 1820 (sensu Poole) with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae, Catocalinae). Quadrifina, 5, 153 - 207." type="journal article" year="2002">Zilli &amp; Hogenes 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
